body:
When I use `@openzeppelin/hardhat-upgrades` to deploy conntracts, I encountered a confusing situation, here it is:
```typscript
    // deploy.ts
    const ITToken = await ethers.getContractFactory('ITToken')
    console.log(await ethers.provider.getTransactionCount(owner.address))
    const itToken1 = await upgrades.deployProxy(ITToken, [])
    console.log(await ethers.provider.getTransactionCount(owner.address))
    const itToken2 = await upgrades.deployProxy(ITToken, [])
    console.log(await ethers.provider.getTransactionCount(owner.address))
```

```cmd
0
ITToken 0x9fE46736679d2D9a65F0992F2272dE9f3c7fa6e0
3
ITToken 0xCf7Ed3AccA5a467e9e704C703E8D87F634fB0Fc9
4
```

see! The second deployed only  has one contract! **Whether there is a configuration to ensure the complete deployment of each execution of deploy.ts? I have a code that predicts the contract address that doesn't work well**, like this: 
ps: targetContract and ProxyAdmin are reused in the second execution, so I have to modifier the nonce to `nocne+1` or reboot network node to ensure `expectPledgeNftPool` is correct...a little annoying...
```typescript
    const expectPledgeNftPool = ethers.utils.getContractAddress({
        from: owner.address,
        nonce: await ethers.provider.getTransactionCount(owner.address) + 3,
    });
```
